r, Yorkshire, England":"Golcar, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Golcar, Metropolitan borough of Kirklees, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Golcar, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Tankersley, Yorkshire, England":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Savile","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Saville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Saville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin; Yorkshire): habitational name from a place in northern France of which the identity is not clear, though it is probably Sainville in Eure-et-Loire, so called from Old French <i>saisne</i> ‘Saxon’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. Compare   Savel  ,   Savell  , and   Savelle  ."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter de Savile was born about 1250, in Golcar, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John de Savile, was 27 and his mother, Agnes, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Maude. He died in 1308, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"Abt 1250–1308":"umbes 1250–1308","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1253–Female":"1253–Surnud","1256–Female":"1256–Surnud","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1284–1336":"1284–1336","1283–Male":"1283–Surnud","1225–1278":"1225–1278","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1249":"1249","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1336":"1336","1225":"1225","1312":"1312","1278":"1278","1256":"1256","1255":"1255","about 1278":"umbes 1278","1308":"1308","Golcar, Yorkshire, England":"Golcar, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Golcar, Metropolitan borough of Kirklees, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Golcar, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tankersley, Yorkshire, England":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1250–1308":"noin 1250–1308","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1253–Female":"1253–Kuollut","1256–Female":"1256–Kuollut","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1284–1336":"1284–1336","1283–Male":"1283–Kuollut","1225–1278":"1225–1278","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1249":"1249","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1336":"1336","1225":"1225","1312":"1312","1278":"1278","1256":"1256","1255":"1255","about 1278":"noin 1278","1308":"1308","Golcar, Yorkshire, England":"Golcar, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Golcar, Metropolitan borough of Kirklees,